<DOC><DOCNO> AP880713-0259 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 0037EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   07-13 0549</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0575</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The nation's drought-battered corn crop mayproduce 5.2 billion bushels this year, 29 percent less thanexpected a few months ago and 26 percent below last year's harvest,the Agriculture Department estimates.   Sharp reductions also are expected in 1988 wheat and soybeanproduction, the department said Tuesday.   Until drought and extreme heat heigthened in May and June, USDAhad projected this year's corn harvest at 7.3 billion bushels, upfrom last year's output of 7.06 billion.</TEXT><DATELINE>WEST HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Coleco Industries Inc., the toymakerwhose fortunes rose and fell with the popularity of Cabbage PatchKids, has conceded defeat in its battle to avoid bankruptcy court.   Coleco said Tuesday it had filed for protection from itscreditors in U.S. Bankruptcy Court for the Southern District of NewYork.   The toymaker also announced that Morton E. Handel, who isrecovering from open-heart surgery, submitted his resignation aschief executive officer because of the company's need for afull-time CEO during this period.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Chrysler Corp. has matched the new, skimpierincentive offerings of General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co. bytrimming back rebates on many models.   Chrysler, the smallest of the Big Three U.S. automakers, hasbeen running incentive campaigns that have no expiration dates. Buttwo weeks ago, it announced its current campaign would expireTuesday.   Industry analysts said at the time that Chrysler was signallingto its two rivals a willingness to reduce the size of rebates andwas giving them a chance to introduce lesser incentives. Ford andGM subsequently did so.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Merrill Lynch andamp; Co. says lower financial marketsactivity contributed to a 36 percent drop in its second-quarterprofit compared with a year earlier.   Merrill Lynch, one of the nation's largest investment houses,said Tuesday its net income totaled $53.5 million, or 47 cents ashare, in the second quarter, compared with earnings of $83.3million, or 75 cents a share, a year earlier.   Chairman William Schreyer said the results were ``reasonableconsidering the difficult business environment experienced duringthe quarter.''</TEXT><DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Aloha Airlines inspectors have confirmed theyfound evidence of corrosion in several of their Boeing 737jetliners years before the April 28 accident in which the top of anAloha jet ripped off over Hawaii.   In one case, a 7{-inch crack was found on a sister ship in thesame section of fuselage that ripped away in April, leaving a largegaping hole above passengers' heads.   Henry Arii, Aloha's vice president for quality control andengineering, said Tuesday the crack was discovered during a routineinspection. Aloha officials blamed the crack on corrosion and saidit was promptly repaired.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   With oil prices falling toward the lowest pointin nearly two years, speculation has grown that influential ArabOPEC producers are flooding the market for political motives thatinclude crushing Iran's diehard war effort and preservingRepublican power in the White House.   Some industry analysts said Tuesday they believe Saudi Arabia,Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates have decided privately thatcheap oil is one of their most effective and plentiful weapons toachieve these aims, despite the enormous revenue losses they couldendure.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>